# Vendored: libheif-js (1.19.8)

## License

This directory contains source code from `libheif-js`, an Emscripten build of
`libheif` distributed as an npm module. Both the wrapper and the underlying
`libheif` library are licensed under the **GNU Lesser General Public License
v3.0** (LGPL-3.0). See `LICENSE` in this directory for the full license text.

LGPL-3.0 is compatible with the project's AGPL-3.0 license (we redistribute the
LGPL portion under LGPL terms; the AGPL applies to our own additions in
`js/vendor/heic-loader.js`).

## What's vendored here

| File                  | Source                                                                | Purpose |
| --------------------- | --------------------------------------------------------------------- | --- |
| `libheif.js` (~80 KB) | `libheif-js@1.19.8` npm tarball, `libheif-wasm/libheif.js`            | Emscripten JS glue. Loaded as a UMD `<script>`, assigns the `libheif` factory to `window.libheif`. |
| `libheif.wasm` (~1.0 MB) | `libheif-js@1.19.8` npm tarball, `libheif-wasm/libheif.wasm`     | The compiled `libheif` WebAssembly module. Fetched on demand by the JS glue (see `locateFile` in `js/vendor/heic-loader.js`). |
| `LICENSE` (~43 KB)    | `libheif-js@1.19.8` npm tarball, `libheif/LICENSE`                    | Full LGPL-3.0 license text. |

## Why the split WASM variant

The upstream package ships three flavors:
1. Pure JS asm.js (`libheif/libheif.js`, ~2.1 MB) — slow, fallback for ancient browsers.
2. Pre-bundled WASM (`libheif-wasm/libheif-bundle.mjs`, ~1.46 MB) — base64-inlines the WASM, adds ~30% size and a boot-time decode hop.
3. Split WASM (`libheif-wasm/libheif.js` + `libheif-wasm/libheif.wasm`, ~80 KB + ~1.0 MB) — what we use here.

The split variant lets the browser stream native WebAssembly bytes instead of
decoding a base64 string. The JS glue calls `locateFile('libheif.wasm')`
exactly once during boot; the loader (`js/vendor/heic-loader.js`) overrides
that callback to point at `/js/vendor/heic/libheif.wasm`. No third-party CDN
at runtime — the WASM is served from this origin.

## Loading discipline

Lazy via dynamic `import()` of `js/vendor/heic-loader.js`, which itself injects
the `<script>` tag for `libheif.js` only when the user attempts to import a
HEIC/HEIF file for the first time. A first-use consent modal (`heic_consent`
key in `localStorage`) discloses the ~1.1 MB download before the request goes
out. The script + WASM are then cached by the browser like any other static
asset.

## Re-vendoring

```bash
# 1. Bump LIBHEIF_VERSION in scripts/install-heic.mjs.
node scripts/install-heic.mjs
# 2. Bump VENDOR_HASH in js/vendor/heic-loader.js so previously-consented
#    users are re-prompted (the on-disk size may have changed).
# 3. Update size lines in THIRD-PARTY.md, privacy.html, and the
#    bgRemoveConsentBody / heicConsentBody i18n strings if the wasm grew.
```

## Brand-stance compliance

At runtime, no third-party CDN is contacted. Every asset path lives under
`/js/vendor/heic/`. This matches the "ad-free, tracker-free, self-hosted"
stance and the privacy panel's disclosure. The 0-byte cost on initial page
load is preserved because `js/vendor/heic-loader.js` lazy-imports the wasm
only after the user opts in to a HEIC import.
